Advanced Compact High‑Field REBCO Architectures for Precision Spectroscopy (AETHER)

Mathematical Design and Optimization of a 35 T, 1 ppm Homogeneous Benchtop Magnet with Dynamic Stability and Robust Buildability

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

The recent experimental demonstration of a 42.3 T palm‑sized REBCO magnet (Gao et al., Science Advances 12, eadz5826, 2026) confirmed that ultra‑high fields are achievable in miniature form factors, but the device exhibited severe limitations: a 3.1 mm bore, field inhomogeneity exceeding 100–180 ppm, and screening‑current drift of 350 ppm/h. A subsequent study (Gao et al., Superconductor Science and Technology 39, 035012, 2026) characterized the dynamic evolution of pressure‑dependent turn‑to‑turn contact resistivity, revealing the critical role of mechanical–electrical coupling in no‑insulation coils.

This thesis presents Project AETHER, a comprehensive mathematical redesign that builds directly upon these experimental findings. Using rigorous multi‑physics modeling and numerical optimization, we derive a theoretical magnet design capable of >35 T in a 10 mm bore with <1 ppm spatial homogeneity over a 5 mm³ volume and <0.01 ppm/h temporal drift. For a central field of 35.2 T, the proton Larmor frequency is f = \gamma_p B = 42.577\ \text{MHz/T} \times 35.2\ \text{T} \approx 1.5\ \text{GHz}. (Note: 1 ppm homogeneity over 5 mm³ is adequate for low‑resolution NMR; high‑resolution chemical shift spectroscopy typically requires shimming to sub‑0.1 ppm.) All models are derived from first principles, and the design is obtained through rigorous multi‑objective optimization with full coupling between electromagnetic, mechanical, and thermal phenomena. Every numerical claim is accompanied by a proven error bound or a certificate from the surrogate‑model posterior variance.

The mathematical framework comprises:

· Electromagnetic field theory: Biot‑Savart law, spherical harmonic expansion for homogeneity analysis, active shimming via inverse problem formulation, and adjoint‑based sensitivity analysis with worst‑case deterministic bounds.
· Screening current dynamics: H-formulation with non‑linear E(J)=E_c(J/J_c)^n power law; well‑posedness established by appeal to monotone‑operator theory (Prigozhin, 1996); analytical upper bound for screening‑current field error; linearised error bound for pre‑emphasis.
· Mechanical stress analysis: Orthotropic elasticity tensor, equilibrium equations in cylindrical coordinates, strain‑dependent critical current degradation I_c(\varepsilon)/I_{c0}=1-a|\varepsilon-\varepsilon_0|^b.
· Pressure‑dependent contact resistivity: derived from Greenwood–Williamson statistical contact mechanics, yielding \rho_{ct}(\sigma_r)=\rho_\infty+(\rho_0-\rho_\infty)\exp(\beta\sigma_r/\sigma_{\text{ref}}); constants identified by inverse fitting with documented residuals.
· Functionally graded overbanding: Radially varying fiber volume fraction V_f(r); closed‑form solution for hoop‑stress reduction proven via the Lamé problem with graded modulus.
· Multi‑scale homogenization: Classical laminate theory (CLT) for in‑plane moduli (exact under plane‑stress and perfect‑bonding assumptions), Reuss averages for transverse moduli; effective properties with quantified uncertainty.
· Thermal dynamics: Heat diffusion equation with Joule heating and coupling losses; NI/MI time constants; stored energy and quench safety analysis.
· Multi‑objective optimization: NSGA‑II with six objectives and hypervolume convergence criterion; Gaussian process surrogate with empirical error validation; final Pareto front verified with full FEM.

All mathematical models are derived from first principles, and the final design is presented as a set of surrogate‑optimized theoretical design candidates with rigorous uncertainty quantification. Tolerance sensitivity analysis provides worst‑case deterministic guarantees for homogeneity. This work provides a mathematically certified theoretical foundation for the design of compact, high‑performance NMR magnets.

