1. Introduction

1.1 Motivation

Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR) spectroscopy is an indispensable tool in chemistry, biology, and materials science, providing atomic‑level information on molecular structure and dynamics. The resolution and sensitivity of NMR scale with the magnetic field strength; higher fields yield greater chemical shift dispersion and improved signal‑to‑noise ratios. The current state‑of‑the‑art employs large‑scale superconducting magnets operating at 1.2 GHz (28.2 T) or hybrid systems reaching 35 T, but these facilities are costly and centrally located. The vision of a benchtop ultra‑high‑field NMR spectrometer—compact and affordable—has long been a goal.

The 2026 breakthrough by Gao et al. demonstrated that palm‑sized REBCO magnets can generate fields exceeding 40 T, opening a path toward miniaturization. However, their device was designed purely for field strength, not field quality. With a bore of only 3.1 mm, inhomogeneity of 100–180 ppm, and temporal drift of 350 ppm/h, it is incapable of resolving chemical shifts. A follow‑up study by the same group (Gao et al., Superconductor Science and Technology 39, 035012, 2026) provided crucial experimental characterization of the dynamic evolution of pressure‑dependent turn‑to‑turn contact resistivity, revealing that mechanical–electrical coupling fundamentally governs charging behavior and temporal stability in no‑insulation coils.

This thesis takes up that challenge, directly building upon these experimental findings to develop a comprehensive mathematical framework for designing a compact, NMR‑grade REBCO magnet. Through rigorous mathematical modeling and numerical optimization, we derive a theoretical magnet architecture that achieves >35 T central field, <1 ppm spatial homogeneity over a 5 mm³ sample volume, and <0.01 ppm/h temporal drift—specifications that would correspond to a 1.5 GHz proton NMR in a benchtop format. The work is purely theoretical; no physical construction or testing is undertaken. All results are presented as mathematically certified design candidates, intended to serve as a foundation for future experimental work.

1.2 Research Objectives

1. Electromagnetic Optimization: Derive a multi‑objective mathematical formulation to maximize field homogeneity while maintaining >35 T central field, incorporating full 2D critical‑state modeling of screening currents with mutual coupling between pancakes.
2. Temporal Stability: Model screening current relaxation using the E(J)=E_c(J/J_c)^n power law to predict field drift, and derive a pre‑emphasis charging profile that achieves dB/dt < 0.01\ \text{ppm/h} over a 1‑hour NMR experiment, with rigorous error bounds.
3. Mechanical Integrity & Dynamic Contact: Derive the equations for a composite overbanding structure with radially varying fiber volume fraction V_f(r) to withstand hoop stresses >1 GPa, incorporating strain‑dependent I_c(\varepsilon) degradation. Formulate pressure‑dependent contact resistivity \rho_{ct}(\sigma_r) from first principles (Greenwood–Williamson) and couple it to the electromagnetic model.
4. Multi‑Scale Tape Modeling: Derive homogenized material properties for REBCO tapes using classical laminate theory.
5. Multi‑Objective Optimization: Implement a surrogate‑assisted multi‑objective optimization framework to explore the design space and identify Pareto‑optimal configurations satisfying all constraints, with certified error estimates.
6. Robust Design: Derive global sensitivity indices (Sobol) to identify critical geometric and material parameters, and formulate a reliability‑based buildability score.

1.3 Thesis Outline

Chapter 2 reviews the state of the art in high‑temperature superconducting magnets, NI/MI coil technology, screening current mitigation, and numerical methods for magnet design. Chapter 3 presents the comprehensive mathematical framework underpinning the AETHER design, covering electromagnetics, mechanics, thermodynamics, and optimization. All proofs and error bounds are integrated into this chapter. Chapter 4 describes the computational implementation and presents the surrogate‑optimized theoretical design candidates, culminating in the final 35 T, 1 ppm magnet with full tolerance sensitivity analysis and certified error estimates. Chapter 5 concludes with a summary of contributions and a discussion of theoretical extensions.

