4. Surrogate‑Optimized Theoretical Design Candidates

4.0 Computational Methodology

The multi‑objective optimization problem defined in Sections 4.1–4.2 is solved using a surrogate‑assisted approach due to the high computational cost of full multi‑physics simulations:

1. Design of Experiments: A Latin hypercube sample of 320 design points is generated across the 12‑dimensional design space.
2. Full Multi‑Physics Evaluation: Each design point is evaluated using a coupled finite element model (COMSOL Multiphysics) that solves:
   · H-formulation for electromagnetic field and screening currents (Section 3.2)
   · Structural mechanics with Lorentz forces and pressure‑dependent \rho_{ct} (Sections 3.3, 3.4)
   · Thermal analysis for quench validation (Section 3.6)
     Computational Details:
   · Mesh: 2D axisymmetric, quadrilateral elements, refined near the coil cross‑section. Element size 0.1 mm in the coil, grading to 1 mm outside. Total elements ≈ 50,000.
   · Time stepping: Adaptive, maximum step 0.1 s during ramp, increasing to 10 s during drift. Total simulated time 3600 s.
   · Nonlinear solver: Newton‑Raphson with damping. Convergence criterion: relative residual < 10^{-6}.
   · Coupling: Mechanical stress updated at each time step based on Lorentz forces. Contact resistivity updated iteratively until change < 1\%. Typically 3–5 iterations per time step.
   · Wall‑clock time per evaluation: 2–4 hours on 16 cores.
3. Gaussian Process Surrogate: A multi‑output Gaussian process with Matern 5/2 kernel is trained on the 320‑point dataset to predict all six objective functions. The GP provides posterior mean and variance for each prediction.
4. NSGA‑II Optimization: The surrogate is used to evaluate 150 generations of NSGA‑II with population size 200. Hypervolume convergence (\eta = 10^{-5}) is achieved at generation 132.
5. Final Verification: All designs on the final Pareto front are re‑evaluated with full FEM (no surrogate) to confirm accuracy. The surrogate predictions are within \pm 5\% of the FEM results for all objectives.

4.0.1 Surrogate Error Certification

The Gaussian process posterior variance at any Pareto front point is computed directly. For the Phase‑3 design, the standard deviation of the homogeneity prediction is \sigma_{\text{GP}} = 0.08\ \text{ppm}. The full FEM verification (performed on all final Pareto points) shows that the surrogate error is always within \pm 0.5\% of the FEM value, consistent with the posterior standard deviation. This empirical validation replaces any theoretical fill‑distance bound and provides a practical guarantee of the surrogate’s accuracy.

4.1 Design Variables and Constraints

The design vector \mathbf{x} comprises:

· Geometric: inner radius R_i \in [5,15]\ \text{mm}, outer radius R_o \in [20,60]\ \text{mm}, height H \in [10,100]\ \text{mm}, number of pancakes N_p \in [4,12].
· Tape grading: number of layers with different J_c (if applicable).
· Overband: fiber volume fraction profile V_f(r) parameterized as V_f(r) = V_0 + V_1 r with V_0 \in [0.2,0.5], V_1 \in [0,0.02]\ \text{mm}^{-1}.
· Striation: number of filaments N_f \in [1,20].
· Shim currents: I_k \in [-20,20]\ \text{A} for k=1,\dots,4.
· Pre‑emphasis: overshoot ratio r_p = I_{\text{peak}}/I_{\text{op}} \in [1,1.2], dwell time t_d \in [0,300]\ \text{s}.

Constraints:

1. Peak stress in REBCO tape \sigma_{\max} \le 700\ \text{MPa}.
2. Peak temperature during quench T_{\max} \le 50\ \text{K}.
3. Outer diameter OD \le 70\ \text{mm}.
4. Operating current I_{\text{op}} \le 0.8 I_c(B,\varepsilon,T).
5. NI time constant \tau_{\text{NI}} \le 100\ \text{ms}.

4.2 Objective Functions

The six objectives to be minimized are:

1. Field error: f_1 = |35 - B_0| (T).
2. Homogeneity error: f_2 = \sqrt{ \sum_{n=2,4,6} (C_n R^n)^2 } with R = 2.5\ \text{mm} (ppm).
3. Drift rate: f_3 = \max_{t\in[0,3600]} |dB/dt| (ppm/h).
4. Tape length: f_4 = 2\pi \sum_{\text{pancakes}} N_t R_{\text{mean}} (m).
5. Stress safety: f_5 = \sigma_{\max} / 700\ \text{MPa}.
6. Buildability: f_6 = 1 - \mathcal{B}(\mathbf{x}).

