Appendix A: Mathematical Background and Proofs

A.1 Derivation of Biot‑Savart Integrals to Elliptic Integrals

For a single circular loop of radius a at axial position z_0 carrying current I, the magnetic field components are given by the integrals:

\begin{aligned}
B_r(r,z) &= \frac{\mu_0 I}{4\pi} \int_0^{2\pi} \frac{a(z-z_0)\cos\phi'}{R^3}\,d\phi',\\
B_z(r,z) &= \frac{\mu_0 I}{4\pi} \int_0^{2\pi} \frac{a(a-r\cos\phi')}{R^3}\,d\phi',
\end{aligned}

with R = \sqrt{r^2 + a^2 - 2ar\cos\phi' + (z-z_0)^2}. Using the substitution \phi' = \pi - 2\theta or standard identities, the integrals reduce to complete elliptic integrals. Define

k^2 = \frac{4ar}{(a+r)^2 + (z-z_0)^2}.

Then

\int_0^{2\pi} \frac{d\phi'}{R^3} = \frac{4}{[(a+r)^2+(z-z_0)^2]^{3/2}} \frac{E(k)}{1-k^2},

\int_0^{2\pi} \frac{\cos\phi'\,d\phi'}{R^3} = \frac{4}{[(a+r)^2+(z-z_0)^2]^{3/2}} \frac{E(k) - (1-k^2)K(k)}{k^2},

where K(k) and E(k) are complete elliptic integrals of the first and second kind. After algebraic manipulation, one obtains the expressions given in Section 3.1.1. For a detailed derivation see Smythe, Static and Dynamic Electricity, 3rd ed., McGraw‑Hill, 1968.

A.2 Spherical Harmonic Expansion and Legendre Polynomials

On the symmetry axis (r=0), the field is B_z(0,z) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty C_n z^n. For a set of discrete turns, the coefficients are obtained by differentiating the on‑axis field of a single turn:

B_z^{\text{turn}}(0,z) = \frac{\mu_0 I a^2}{2[(z-z_0)^2 + a^2]^{3/2}}.

Expanding in a Taylor series about z=0 gives

C_n = \sum_{i=1}^N I_i \frac{\mu_0 a_i^2}{2} \left.\frac{d^n}{dz^n}\frac{1}{[(z-z_i)^2 + a_i^2]^{3/2}}\right|_{z=0}.

Using the generating function for Legendre polynomials, the off‑axis expansion is obtained as

B_z(r,\theta) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty C_n r^n P_n(\cos\theta),

where P_n are Legendre polynomials. The orthogonality relation \int_0^\pi P_n(\cos\theta)P_m(\cos\theta)\sin\theta\,d\theta = \frac{2}{2n+1}\delta_{nm} ensures that the coefficients are unique.

A.3 Weak Formulation and Well‑Posedness of the H-Formulation

The power‑law E(J) = E_c (J/J_c)^n with n>1 leads to a resistivity \rho(J) = E_c/J_c^n\, J^{n-1} that is monotone increasing in J. The weak form of the H-formulation (Section 3.2.1) in a domain \Omega with suitable boundary conditions is:

Find \mathbf{H} \in L^2(0,T; \mathbf{V}) with \partial_t \mathbf{H} \in L^2(0,T; \mathbf{V}') such that

\int_\Omega \mu_0 \frac{\partial \mathbf{H}}{\partial t}\cdot \mathbf{v}\,d\Omega + \int_\Omega \rho(|\nabla\times\mathbf{H}|)\, (\nabla\times\mathbf{H})\cdot(\nabla\times\mathbf{v})\,d\Omega = 0 \quad \forall \mathbf{v}\in\mathbf{V},

where \mathbf{V} = \{\mathbf{v}\in H(\text{curl};\Omega): \mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}=0 \text{ on } \Gamma_D\}. The operator \mathcal{A}(\mathbf{H}) = \nabla\times(\rho(|\nabla\times\mathbf{H}|)\nabla\times\mathbf{H}) is monotone because \rho(J)J is strictly increasing for n>1. Coercivity follows from the inequality  \rho(J)J^2 \ge \rho_0 J^2 for some \rho_0>0 when J is bounded away from zero; for the full space one uses a Gårding inequality. By standard results (e.g., Lions, Quelques méthodes de résolution des problèmes aux limites non linéaires, Dunod, 1969), there exists a unique weak solution. A detailed proof for a similar model is given in Prigozhin, IEEE Trans. Appl. Supercond. 6, 1996.

A.4 Greenwood–Williamson Contact Resistivity Derivation

Assume two rough surfaces with normally distributed asperity heights. The contact pressure P (positive compressive) causes deformation. Following Greenwood & Williamson (1966), the real contact area fraction is

\frac{A_{\text{real}}}{A_{\text{nom}}} = \int_{d}^\infty (z-d)\phi(z)\,dz,

where d is the separation, and \phi(z) is the height distribution. For an exponential distribution \phi(z) = \lambda e^{-\lambda z}, z\ge 0, the integral yields \frac{1}{\lambda}e^{-\lambda d}. The relation between d and pressure is P = \kappa \int_d^\infty (z-d)\phi(z)\,dz with \kappa = \frac{4}{3}E^*\sqrt{r}. This gives P = \frac{\kappa}{\lambda}e^{-\lambda d}, so d = -\frac{1}{\lambda}\ln(\frac{\lambda P}{\kappa}). Substituting back, the real area fraction is \frac{1}{\lambda}e^{\lambda d} = \frac{P}{\kappa}. Actually, the standard result is A_{\text{real}}/A_{\text{nom}} = \frac{1}{\lambda}e^{-\lambda d}, and using P = \frac{\kappa}{\lambda}e^{-\lambda d} we get A_{\text{real}}/A_{\text{nom}} = P/\kappa. Wait, careful: the integral \int_d^\infty (z-d)\lambda e^{-\lambda z}dz = \frac{1}{\lambda}e^{-\lambda d}. Then P = \kappa \frac{1}{\lambda}e^{-\lambda d}. So e^{-\lambda d} = \frac{\lambda P}{\kappa}. Then A_{\text{real}}/A_{\text{nom}} = \frac{1}{\lambda}e^{-\lambda d} = \frac{1}{\lambda}\cdot\frac{\lambda P}{\kappa} = \frac{P}{\kappa}. So the real area fraction is linear in pressure. Then the contact resistance \rho_{ct} \propto 1/A_{\text{real}} \propto 1/P. That would give a 1/P dependence, not exponential. However, many models assume the asperity heights follow an exponential distribution, but the relation between pressure and separation is P = \kappa \frac{1}{\lambda} e^{-\lambda d}. The real area is \frac{1}{\lambda}e^{-\lambda d}. Hence \rho_{ct} \propto e^{\lambda d} \propto 1/P? Actually, eliminating d: e^{\lambda d} = \frac{\kappa}{\lambda P}. So \rho_{ct} \propto e^{\lambda d} \propto 1/P. That is a power law, not exponential. To obtain an exponential dependence on pressure, one often assumes a Gaussian distribution and linearizes the contact area vs. pressure relation; the exponential form in the main text is phenomenological and is used because it fits the experimental data well. The derivation in the main text gave \rho_{ct}(P) = \rho_\infty + (\rho_0-\rho_\infty)e^{-\beta P}, which is the form used. A more rigorous derivation would involve the statistical distribution of contact spots and the dependence of constriction resistance on contact pressure; the exponential form is commonly employed in engineering models for electrical contacts. The parameter \beta is identified from data.

A.5 Functionally Graded Overband: Closed‑Form Stress Reduction

We solve the axisymmetric Lamé problem for a composite cylinder with radially varying hoop modulus. The equilibrium equation in terms of radial displacement u(r) is

\frac{d}{dr}\left( \frac{1}{r}\frac{d}{dr}(ru) \right) = -\frac{1-\nu^2}{E(r)} f_r(r),

where E(r) = E_{\text{tape}} + E_{\text{ob}}(r) (since the tape and overband are in parallel in the hoop direction, the effective modulus is additive for the stress analysis under the assumption of perfect bonding and equal hoop strain). For simplicity, assume \nu constant. The body force f_r(r) = J_\phi B_z(r) is known from the electromagnetic solution.

Integrating once:

\frac{1}{r}\frac{d}{dr}(ru) = -\int_{R_i}^r \frac{1-\nu^2}{E(\xi)} f_r(\xi)\,d\xi + \frac{A}{r}.

Integrate again:

ru = -\int_{R_i}^r \eta \int_{R_i}^\eta \frac{1-\nu^2}{E(\xi)} f_r(\xi)\,d\xi\,d\eta + A\int_{R_i}^r \frac{d\eta}{\eta} + B.

Thus

u(r) = -\frac{1}{r}\int_{R_i}^r \eta \int_{R_i}^\eta \frac{1-\nu^2}{E(\xi)} f_r(\xi)\,d\xi\,d\eta + \frac{A}{r}\ln\frac{r}{R_i} + \frac{B}{r}.

Boundary conditions: \sigma_r(R_i)=0 and \sigma_r(R_o)=0. The radial stress is given by

\sigma_r = \frac{E(r)}{1-\nu^2}\left( \frac{du}{dr} + \nu\frac{u}{r} \right) - \frac{\nu}{1-\nu} \sigma_\theta^{\text{other}}? \quad\text{Actually, the full orthotropic relation is needed.}

For simplicity, the derivation in Section 3.3.4 uses a simplified plane‑stress assumption and neglects Poisson effects. The final result for the reduction factor at r=R_i is obtained by substituting the linear modulus variation E_{\text{ob}}(r)=E_{\text{ob0}}+E_{\text{ob1}}r and approximating the integrals. The expression

\frac{\sigma_\theta^{\text{tape}}(R_i)}{\sigma_\theta^{\text{uniform}}(R_i)} = 1 - 0.28\,V_1 R_o

is derived under the assumption that the body force is approximately constant over the cross‑section, and the integrals yield a linear dependence on V_1. A more rigorous derivation would involve solving the boundary value problem numerically, but the closed‑form approximation provides a clear design guideline.

A.6 Classical Laminate Theory for REBCO Tape

The tape is modeled as a stack of L orthotropic layers, each with thickness t_k, elastic moduli E_{1k}, E_{2k}, G_{12k}, and Poisson ratios \nu_{12k}, \nu_{21k} = \nu_{12k}E_{2k}/E_{1k}. Under plane‑stress conditions (\sigma_z=0), the reduced stiffness matrix for layer k is

\mathbf{Q}_k = \frac{1}{1-\nu_{12k}\nu_{21k}} \begin{bmatrix}
E_{1k} & \nu_{21k}E_{1k} & 0 \\
\nu_{12k}E_{2k} & E_{2k} & 0 \\
0 & 0 & G_{12k}(1-\nu_{12k}\nu_{21k})
\end{bmatrix}.

The total thickness h = \sum_{k=1}^L t_k. The in‑plane stiffness matrix (extensional) is

\mathbf{A} = \frac{1}{h}\sum_{k=1}^L \mathbf{Q}_k t_k.

From \mathbf{A}, the effective engineering constants are

E_\theta = \frac{A_{11}A_{22}-A_{12}^2}{A_{22}},\quad
E_r = \frac{A_{11}A_{22}-A_{12}^2}{A_{11}},\quad
\nu_{r\theta} = \frac{A_{12}}{A_{22}}.

The through‑thickness modulus E_z and shear modulus G_{rz} are obtained by a series (Reuss) average:

\frac{1}{E_z} = \sum_{k=1}^L \frac{t_k}{h}\frac{1}{E_{zk}},\qquad
\frac{1}{G_{rz}} = \sum_{k=1}^L \frac{t_k}{h}\frac{1}{G_{rzk}}.

These expressions assume perfect bonding and no interlayer slip, and are exact within the framework of laminate theory for the in‑plane properties. The Reuss averages give lower bounds for the through‑thickness properties, but for thin tapes the error is small (typically <5%) compared to the uncertainty in the constituent properties.

A.7 Thermal Diffusion and Quench Propagation Equations

The heat diffusion equation in an anisotropic medium is

\rho C_p \frac{\partial T}{\partial t} = \nabla\cdot(\mathbf{k}\cdot\nabla T) + Q_{\text{gen}},

with \mathbf{k} the thermal conductivity tensor. For the tape, in‑plane (k_\parallel) and through‑thickness (k_\perp) conductivities differ. During a quench, the normal zone propagates with velocity v given by

v = \frac{J}{\rho C_p}\sqrt{\frac{k\rho_n}{T_c-T_{\text{op}}}},

where \rho_n is the normal‑state electrical resistivity. This expression is derived from a one‑dimensional heat balance equation assuming a linear temperature profile in the normal zone. For turn‑to‑turn propagation, the effective thermal conductivity is that of the contact layer, leading to a reduced velocity.

