Appendix C: Numerical Implementation Details

C.1 Finite Element Mesh Convergence Study

A mesh convergence study was performed on a representative coil geometry. The H-formulation with full coupling was solved on meshes with element sizes ranging from 0.2 mm to 0.05 mm in the coil region. The central field, peak stress, and drift rate were monitored. A mesh with 0.1 mm elements in the coil (≈50,000 elements) gave results within 0.5% of the finest mesh (0.05 mm, ≈200,000 elements). All reported results use the 0.1 mm mesh.

C.2 Time Stepping and Nonlinear Solver Settings

Time discretization: adaptive backward Euler with maximum step size 0.1 s during the ramp and 10 s during the hold. The nonlinear system is solved with a Newton‑Raphson method; damping factor 0.5 is applied when the residual does not decrease. Convergence criterion: relative residual < 10⁻⁶. The coupled mechanical‑electrical iteration uses fixed‑point with under‑relaxation factor 0.7; typically 3–5 iterations per time step.

C.3 Surrogate Model Training and Validation

A multi‑output Gaussian process (GP) with Matern 5/2 kernel was implemented using the GPyTorch library. The input design space (12 dimensions) was normalized to [0,1]. Hyperparameters were optimized by maximizing the marginal likelihood. Leave‑one‑out cross‑validation gave a mean absolute error of 2.3% for the homogeneity objective and 3.1% for the drift objective. The final Pareto front was re‑evaluated with full FEM; the maximum relative error between GP prediction and FEM was 4.8% for any objective.

