Appendix D: Additional Sensitivity Analysis

D.1 Sobol Index Computation Methodology

Sobol total sensitivity indices were computed using the Saltelli estimator with N = 10^4 samples from the GP surrogate. The sampling scheme uses two independent Latin hypercube samples of size N and then constructs N(d+2) evaluations to compute first‑order and total indices. Convergence was checked by increasing N to 2\times10^4; indices changed by less than 0.02.

D.2 Worst‑Case Bounds for Homogeneity

The worst‑case deterministic bound for homogeneity error is obtained by assuming each geometric parameter can deviate by \delta_i = 3\sigma_i (99.7% confidence interval). Using the first‑order sensitivity derivatives \partial C_n/\partial\xi_i computed via adjoint methods, the maximum possible coefficient is

|C_n|_{\max} = |C_n(0)| + \sum_i \left|\frac{\partial C_n}{\partial\xi_i}\right| \delta_i.

The worst‑case homogeneity error is then \sqrt{\sum_n (|C_n|_{\max} R^n)^2}. For Phase‑3, this gives 0.97 ppm, confirming that the design meets the <1 ppm specification even under worst‑case manufacturing tolerances.

